NAME
       grep - print lines matching a pattern

SYNOPSIS
       grep [-cEFHhilnqrRsvx] [-e PATTERN] PATTERN [FILE ...]

DESCRIPTION
       Reads each FILE (or stdin) line-by-line and prints lines that
       match PATTERN. By default PATTERN is a basic regular expression
       (BRE) compiled by the libcervus regex(3) engine.

OPTIONS
       -c          print only a count of matching lines per file
       -E          interpret PATTERN as an extended regex (ERE)
       -F          interpret PATTERN as a fixed string, no regex
       -H          force filename prefix on each match
       -h          suppress filename prefix
       -i          case-insensitive match
       -l          print only filenames containing any match
       -n          prefix each match with its line number
       -q          quiet; exit 0 as soon as a match is found
       -r, -R      recurse into directories
       -s          suppress error messages
       -v          invert match
       -x          match whole lines

EXIT STATUS
       0    at least one line matched
       1    no lines matched
       2    incorrect usage or bad pattern

EXAMPLES
       grep -n main *.c
       grep -rE '\\b[Ee]rror\\b' /var/log
       grep -F '#include' file.c

SEE ALSO
       find(1), regex(3)
